<StringTableFile xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xmlns:xsd="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema">
  <Name>conversations\companions\companion_cv_durance_v2</Name>
  <NextEntryID>1</NextEntryID>
  <EntryCount>129</EntryCount>
  <Entries>
    <Entry>
      <ID>5</ID>
      <DefaultText>Squatting at the base of this statue is an incredibly ugly man, with bulging red cheeks raked by pox scars, and a scraggly beard. He is sweating, as if he has a fever, but his breathing is measured and steady... like a slow push of a blacksmith's bellows, but that comparison feels strange and unwelcome.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>6</ID>
      <DefaultText>The next comparison, possibly sparked by his grin, is that of a bear trap... and then out of nowhere, there is the hint of alchemical fire... that fades almost as soon as you identify the smell.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>7</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Come to pray at the statue?"

The question mark is barely there. As the man makes the statement, the statue takes on a reddish cast, as if one is holding a torch to it, then slowly blossoms into waving flames. The man doesn't turn as the statue blossoms into fire.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>8</ID>
      <DefaultText>"The others are welcome, but it's best if just you and I trade words, and your shadows stay quiet, hands off their weapons - both arcane and steel."

His face tenses with his iron bear trap smile, ready to spring. "It's only you I want to trade words with anyway."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>9</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Traveling by yourself." The tone is approving. "It's best you and I trade words, and your hands lay off your weapons - arcane and steel." 

The tension in his face relaxes, and the bear trap grin fades. "It's only you I want to trade words with anyway."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>10</ID>
      <DefaultText>"I swear before the whore that is Magran no harm will come to you in her shadow, if that's enough of a promise for you. If not..."

A staff rests easily in his hand - it wasn't there a moment ago.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>11</ID>
      <DefaultText>"The whore that is Magran?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>12</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Your choice of words - that is my faith you heap insults upon."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>13</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Strange choice of company. Stone seems cold comfort."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>14</ID>
      <DefaultText>[Examine the statue.]</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>15</ID>
      <DefaultText>[Study the man.]</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>16</ID>
      <DefaultText>[Focus your gaze on the staff.]</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>17</ID>
      <DefaultText>"I didn't catch your name - or why you want to speak with me."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>18</ID>
      <DefaultText>[Leave] "I have no need to trade words with you."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>19</ID>
      <DefaultText>The weaving firelight from the statue gives off no heat, so much so, you wonder if it is some trick of the mind... the ugly man before you doesn't seem to notice it, or feel it, although the sheen on his brow is still present, as if he's burning up from within.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>20</ID>
      <DefaultText>The man smiles slightly at your words... then nods, never taking his eyes off you. "I could do better. Though the road holds little... else." His eyes run the length of your frame, and he follows it with a sneer. "Until now."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>21</ID>
      <DefaultText>"The world holds many whores we worship. Respect comes with honest titles.
 
"I'll bet even you have gone against instinct in exchange for a little copper... or paid for such, in countless ways."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>22</ID>
      <DefaultText>The man shrugs, so casual as to add a further insult with its dismissiveness. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>23</ID>
      <DefaultText>"But if I give offense..." The man's face cracks a smile with teeth, almost a dare. "If words are all that are left to a man - then why, in the Dyrwood of all places, he should have leave to speak them."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>24</ID>
      <DefaultText>The sudden weaving flames from the statue of Magran cast more light on his features. The man's robes are dirty, stained with grease, and other marks of the road...
 
The hems of his robes, including the sleeves, are burned at the edges, as if he walked a great distance across a fire, then reached into the flames with his hands to pull something out. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>25</ID>
      <DefaultText>But while his hands are thick and callused, they bear no burn or scorch marks.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>26</ID>
      <DefaultText>The staff looks thick, stout, of blackened ash once burned by a terrible fire. Beneath the ash, the lines in the wood bear shapes and patterns... and there is a certainty the staff was once something far more dangerous... but not now.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>27</ID>
      <DefaultText>As you study it deeper, it shimmers slightly in your eyes, like water catching the light weaving across the statue. Whatever power was bled from the staff, it doesn't make it - or the wielder - any less dangerous.

You look up to see the man watching you studying the staff. As his gaze meets yours, he nods with a humorless smile.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>28</ID>
      <DefaultText>"I didn't give it." The man grunts. "You probably find names as useless as I do..." His hand tightens around the staff. 

"The names that litter this world like debris are hard enough to wrap around the tongue, and what do they matter?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>29</ID>
      <DefaultText>"It's what's beneath the skin and the letters I care about, what burns within. It's more important to me you're a Watcher than whatever culture or accent decorates your letters like awkward crowns.

"Take pride in your actions, not where you hail from..." The man's staff blossoms with fire for a moment, then the embers settle. "...or how your name rolls off whatever liar's tongue coats it now."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>30</ID>
      <DefaultText>"If you need a title to hang on me to match your own, Watcher, then call me Durance. And as you observe souls, I test them."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>31</ID>
      <DefaultText>"How did you know I was a Watcher?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>32</ID>
      <DefaultText>"What do you mean?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>33</ID>
      <DefaultText>"How did you come here?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>34</ID>
      <DefaultText>"I think we've traded enough words."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>35</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Not nearly enough by my count. I know what you are... it's only fair that you know me as well, if your sight hasn't already told you."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>36</ID>
      <DefaultText>"I am a missionary. I walk this diseased nation, with its heathen, its people so careless with the spirits of others and their own. Watchers, among them. 

"Yes, I know you for what you are, and your name doesn't interest me. Names are for honest folk, and you are a crack that shines light from... another place."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>37</ID>
      <DefaultText>Durance shakes his head, and his hand curls tightly on his staff. "I can see the questions bubbling up. Let's burn them away, one by one."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>38</ID>
      <DefaultText>"We're meant to travel together, you and I. Saw you in the flames... not your face, but that soul of yours." He grunts again, his eyes narrowing. "All tightened up like a huntsman's knot."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>39</ID>
      <DefaultText>"You saw my soul in the flames?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>40</ID>
      <DefaultText>"And what is it you think you can offer me?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>41</ID>
      <DefaultText>"I don't want your company."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>42</ID>
      <DefaultText>"There's things we can teach each other, if you're in need of answers to your mantle of questions."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>43</ID>
      <DefaultText>"I don't force my words on anyone other than you. I don't care who walks with you or what their mewling problems and politics are... there's enough howling in the world without me stoking that fire.

"I won't take from your provisions, don't need much on the road. I can carry my weight..." he inhales, again giving you the impression of a blacksmith bellows, and he smiles, almost proudly. "Which is considerable."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>44</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Many will stand against you." He stares at you for a moment, his brow creasing. "They probably already have, from what I can see... left their marks, it seems, like a trail, worming its way behind you."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>45</ID>
      <DefaultText>"What kind of marks?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>46</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Company would be welcome on the road."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>47</ID>
      <DefaultText>"If your stone mistress there allows it, then come on."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>48</ID>
      <DefaultText>"I have no need of your help."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>49</ID>
      <DefaultText>He stares at your face, then into your eyes â€“ almost dully at first, then more intently. "Disease? Spirit wind?" He shrugs. "Both could have touched you, yet here you stand."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>50</ID>
      <DefaultText>"As for disease..." He taps the pox scars on his face. "Not all of us were close to water when the pox hit, but it's no longer a passenger in my flesh. It left its marks as well. 

"But like flames, the pox doesn't strike twice, nor is it catching."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>51</ID>
      <DefaultText>"You think me a burden?" Durance's face twists into a sneer. "I'm here to help you, Watcher. And you can help me with nothing more than letting me walk with you.

"I'm no stranger to battle, if that's your fear. And if you need, I can tend wounds, and give counsel... but both only if you ask for it."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>52</ID>
      <DefaultText>"As I said, I have no need of your help. Farewell."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>53</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Her?" Durance glances at the statue, then gives a low chuckle. "Don't fear her jealousy." His chuckle dies into a smile, a genuine one. "Let us see what the road holds, Watcher."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>54</ID>
      <DefaultText>Durance face cracks into a smile. "Then let us walk together, Watcher."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>55</ID>
      <DefaultText>Durance tenses, and his hand tightens on his staff.

He looks as if he's about to say something, then relaxes.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>56</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Watcher." Durance turns his pox-scarred face to yours, his eyes burning, almost eagerly. "I thought you might see differently. Here again, the three of us - you, me, and the whore. Have you changed your mind?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>57</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Thought I felt your eyes on me. Now come the words."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>58</ID>
      <DefaultText>"And what must you say now?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>59</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Does something ail you?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>60</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Your face is full of need." Durance snorts. "It looks to burst if you didn't speak."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>61</ID>
      <DefaultText>"I had questions I wanted to ask you."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>62</ID>
      <DefaultText>"I need you to leave."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>63</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Let's travel together again."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>64</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Never mind. Let's be going."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>99</ID>
      <DefaultText>Durance doesn't seem to recognize you for a second, then blinks, frowns. "What is it, Watcher?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>100</ID>
      <DefaultText>"You've cast aside my name. Have I offended you?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>101</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Are you all right?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>102</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Does what we learned about Woedica trouble you?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>103</ID>
      <DefaultText>"This... this machination of Woedica." A bead of sweat travels down Durance's forehead, then travels downwards, tracing the edges of his pox scars. "Do you trust in the truth of it?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>104</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Yes."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>105</ID>
      <DefaultText>"I'm not sure."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>106</ID>
      <DefaultText>"I don't."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>107</ID>
      <DefaultText>"It stinks of her... it is justice... but... if her greater purpose was..." His face contorts in fury. "To think Magran would fall prey to such deceit..."

"And Eothas... Waidwen had always claimed to be invading Dyrwood to FREE it. What if it were true? What if he had come to stop Woedica's plot before it began?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>108</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Surely, Eothas earned his death at Godhammer Citadel, but not for those reasons... not to keep him silent.

"If such a thing has brought about this chaos..." Durance tilts his head, as if listening to an inner voice... then he frowns, the frown deepening as he speaks.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>109</ID>
      <DefaultText>Durance face collapses in fury, his body shaking. "Must we always be tools of Gods?! If Woedica... and Magran... if they are the cause for this... the Hollowborn... if the purges were never necessary... if Eothas was fighting back..."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>110</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Then your... 'Godhammer' didn't save Dyrwood. It doomed it."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>111</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Eothas needed to be stopped. And so does Woedica."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>112</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Whatever the reason, Eothas still sought to murder others, inflict his will on others."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>113</ID>
      <DefaultText>"The Hollowborn were the crime of another god."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>114</ID>
      <DefaultText>"The Purges?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>115</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Would it have been better had you been spared this knowledge?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>116</ID>
      <DefaultText>"It is a lot to take in."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>118</ID>
      <DefaultText>"So many lies..." Durance's body continues to shake, his hands clenching white into fists. Sweat builds, streaming down the sides of his face. "...and Woedica... perhaps she is the next god to fall beneath the Godhammer."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>119</ID>
      <DefaultText>Durance stiffens, and he takes in a long, slow breath, steadying himself. 

"I know." Durance seems to... sag, for a moment. "It had to be done."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>120</ID>
      <DefaultText>Durance stiffens, and he takes in a long, slow breath, steadying himself. 

"I know." Durance sighs. "It had to be done... yet... there would have been times I would have stayed my hand."
 
His face darkens. "Woedica... she must answer to her own justice."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>121</ID>
      <DefaultText>"No..." Durance is cold. "It... I am glad to have walked this far with you, seen this truth..."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>122</ID>
      <DefaultText>"...perhaps it is what I was meant to see." He glances at you beneath his brows, warily. "With a Watcher's eyes."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>123</ID>
      <DefaultText>"All these dances of words and intrigues... machines of men, twisted... ripping the souls of children. And by the gods. The goddess of justice.

"If I could end her like Eothas... I..." He takes a breath, his eyes narrowing. "Magran burned her once. One can do so again."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>124</ID>
      <DefaultText>His face darkens. "Woedica... she must answer to her own justice." </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>125</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Justice? Or revenge?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>126</ID>
      <DefaultText>"These acts... feel more akin to Woedica's aspect, her true aspect - or Skaen's."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>127</ID>
      <DefaultText>"No..." Durance is cold. "No, it is not. It... I am glad to have walked this far with you, seen this truth..."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>128</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Any one with any shred of spirit seeks both justice and punishment, it burns in the heart of any one who lives." Durance frowns, his hands clenching. "All seek it."

"If the world does not balance, we'd all drown in the oceans... and the gods would not care.

"Magran - she must be redeemed, and punishing Woedica... that will serve." </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>129</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Do we know that Magran was not a willing accomplice?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>131</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Magran was allied with Woedica. She tried to kill all the makers of the Godhammer."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>132</ID>
      <DefaultText>Durance looks at you for a moment, then his lip peels back, sneering. "Is this some final joke at my expense? To test my faith further?" He laughs, loud and harsh. "And why would you think that, Watcher?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>133</ID>
      <DefaultText>"I'm not certain - it's just a feeling I have."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>135</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Because she didn't want anyone to know how the Godhammer had been made. No one knows how it came to be, except few among Magran... like yourself."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>136</ID>
      <DefaultText>"When you departed for Halgot Citadel to strike at Eothas, you traveled so no one could recognize you, correct?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>137</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Why would the goddess of war cloak her soldiers when they leave her seat at Ashfall?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>138</ID>
      <DefaultText>"You said you left Ashfall without telling anyone of your departure?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>139</ID>
      <DefaultText>"The others who made the Godhammer. They all died, didn't they? That's why I saw their symbols fade from your staff."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>140</ID>
      <DefaultText>Durance laughs again. "That is all you have? A feeling?" He snarls. "If feelings provoked me to say every thought that crossed my mind..." He shakes his head. "Get gone, and leave me to my thoughts."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>141</ID>
      <DefaultText>Durance frowns - and his smile dies as he stares at you. "If all you have are questions, then I have enough of those. She is a bitch of a goddess to be sure... but even a whore only goes so far in crossing those she serves."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>142</ID>
      <DefaultText>Durance is silent for a moment, and when he speaks again, he speaks low and slowly, almost carefully. "You answer a question with a question." He frowns. "Then why did I feel her disappointment at Halgot? Why were we shamed?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>143</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Because I think she tried to kill you there."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>144</ID>
      <DefaultText>Durance looks at you for a moment as if you're mad, then his lip peels back, sneering. "Kill me?" He laughs, loud and harsh.

"She is a goddess. I still drink from her burning breasts, Watcher." His face burns, and his hand clenches tight on the staff. "If she wished me dead, she could trace me to my source and kill me."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>146</ID>
      <DefaultText>"In the dream of the Godhammer, your spirit looked... blurred, indistinct in the light. As if it had been sheared from you."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>147</ID>
      <DefaultText>Durance stares at you, his expression frozen - but he's silent, listening.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>148</ID>
      <DefaultText>"When we petitioned her, she didn't recognize you - you know it."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>151</ID>
      <DefaultText>"If you had been damaged as I saw in the Godhammer vision, then she may be unable to see you as you once were."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>152</ID>
      <DefaultText>Durance turns from you for a moment. His face twists in thought, conflicting emotions running across his features. 

Finally, he turns to you, his face steady.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>153</ID>
      <DefaultText>"If you don't trust me, then trust your staff. Admit that the other Godhammer builders are dead."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>155</ID>
      <DefaultText>Durance turns to the staff, and for a moment, you see his eyes burning, taking in the edges of the wood, the symbols inlaid there... the eleven faded circles... </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>156</ID>
      <DefaultText>When your vision clears, you see Durance, his hands clutching the staff, and his eyes are bright, burning red. Atop the staff, the flame burns cleanly, brightly. As his gaze burns, he rips his gaze away and howls, a bellowing horrid howl, like a wounded animal, and sweat pours down his brow.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>157</ID>
      <DefaultText>As he studies the staff, you feel a wave of heat, a terrible energy rolling forth from it in waves, so much so it feels as if the Godhammer itself is alive in his hands... and past it, you hear a cry, like a child being born, and your eyes feel the flash of white, then a hundred imagined shades of purple and white, streaming and circling into the howling of a storm, and beneath it, the grinding of ancient machines of stone, rock, and metal... grinding and turning until all around you feels as if it's burning, sinking into the shadows of the earth... beneath the ground, the only place where a spirit might find refuge.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>158</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Durance, we can make this right."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>159</ID>
      <DefaultText>"We can see that justice is served - to her and Woedica both."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>160</ID>
      <DefaultText>"This is not over. We still have much to do."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>161</ID>
      <DefaultText>"To think... I served her. I followed her." Durance's face cracks into a snarl. "Now, I shall serve no one. Woedica's lies must be answered... and now it seems I must take fire and war from a goddess' false claim as well."

His face becomes stone, his eyes still burning, almost hungrily. "I still take from her strength as I did... for as long as it lasts." Durance snarls. "For I shall not cast her aside yet until I have drained her dry and had my fill... just as she intended for me."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>162</ID>
      <DefaultText>"For I have learned one of the lessons of the 'faithful' - the faithful may wound a goddess greater than any enemy - a purification is coming, and this fire shall consume them both."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>163</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Let's continue on."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>165</ID>
      <DefaultText>Trigger Conv Node 165</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>166</ID>
      <DefaultText>Trigger Conv Node 166</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>172</ID>
      <DefaultText>"They died in the blast, yes. The other eleven. I was the only one to walk away. I thought... we had wronged our goddess... that this was my trial, and if I could prove myself worthy... Worthy of HER! 

"I should've known better. There is only one god of redemption, and I saw him ended."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>176</ID>
      <DefaultText>"There's no proof, Watcher. I was a fool to think you could help me see any farther than I could."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>177</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Then... here I'll stay, Watcher. If you see differently, come again."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>178</ID>
      <DefaultText>"The end of the road greets us at last. You fared well, Watcher." His eyes narrow. "Better than any Watcher has right to.

"Seems you were a field in need of a flame's cleansing."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>179</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Would that my own trial had produced such an outcome. I had myself figured for the field all this time, but you were the field, and I the darkness. A lesson neither of Durance nor of Magran.

"But with that trial's end, a new one begins. A god's trial. And I will stand in judgment without mercy."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
